ned to the streets and draws a vivid picture of the social milieu that shaped their choices. The Devil’s Chain demonstrates that discussions of prostitution and its attendant disorders—sexual deviancy, alcoholism, child abuse, vagrancy, and other related problems—reflected differing visions for the future of the Polish nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aProstitutionzPolandxHistoryy19th century. 0aProstitutionzPolandxHistoryy20th century. 0aSexxSocial aspectszPolandxHistoryy19th century. 0aSexxSocial aspectszPolandxHistoryy20th century. 4aEurope. 4aHistory.  aPoland, political independence, sex industry, commercial sex, prostitution, home-grown prostitution, paid sex, social control, sexuality, gender propriety, social class, transition to modernity, social reformers, Polish history, history of sexuality, urbanization, migration, professionalization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170166540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501701665423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501701665/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles